subSection.paragraph:
Iris domestica

(L.) Goldblatt & Mabb [the name 

Belamcanda chinensis

(L.) DC (
Iridaceae
) was recorded in Chinese Pharmacopoeia for 2020] belongs to the family 
Iridaceae
and is widely distributed in eastern Asia. Its rhizomes have been historically used as a traditional Chinese folk medicine to treat sore throat, cough, tonsillitis and pharyngitis (
Zhang et al., 2016
). Pharmacological research has shown that 

I. domestica

is often used with other herbs as antipyretic agents, antidotes, expectorants, antiphlogistics, and analgesics (
Xin et al., 2015
). Prior phytochemical investigation of this plant demonstrates that flavonoids, especially isoflavones, are the primary active ingredient of 

I. domestica

(Wo´zniak and Matkowski, 2015). Isoflavones and their glycosides, such as tectorigenin, irigenin, tectoridin, iridin, and irisflorentin, possess a wide range of biological activities, such as anti-inflammatory (
Lim et al., 2018
), antioxidative (
Noh et al., 2018
), antiviral (
Farag et al., 2009
), antibacterial (
Oh et al., 2001
), and antitumor (
Thelen et al., 2005
) activities. However, the applications of diverse and bioactive flavones are often limited by their poor solubility in both hydrophobic and hydrophilic media. Therefore, modification of flavonoid glycosides via acylation has become a promising approach. Previous studies have shown that fatty acid acylated flavonoid glycosides improve the lipophilicity, and biological activities of the parent flavones (

Sudan
and Rupasinghe, 2015

; 
Xin et al., 2019
; 
Bhullar et al., 2014
; 
Warnakulasuriya et al., 2016a
,b; 
Sekhon-Loodu et al., 2015
).

Additional material (1D and 2D NMR, UV, IR, HRESIMS spectra of compounds 
1–6
) is provided in the Supporting Information.
